Permutation Tests

In the permutation test, positive values from BVA for same time-windows were extracted, corresponding to the area of ipsi-contra rather than contra-ipsi. These values are transformed to the negative (*-1) and combined with original samples to a combined 42 or 34 negative values, respective of experiment. Then, 100k samples size 21 or 17 (depending on the experiment) are drawn from the combined pools. If left/right position of channel (contra/ipsi target-channel relationship) is meaningful, then observed value should be in the higher 5% of the distribution of permuted means. The dashed line marks the probability of the original mean within the distribution of permuted means. The number next to the line shows the probability of the original mean within the distribution of permuted means.

SPCN: The results of the permutation tests show low probability of meaningful negativity in all conditions of Experiment 1, with trends evident following a valid cue for the lateral target and salient target conditions, and no distractor following a neutral cue (ps = 0.07). On the other hand, in Experiment 2, probability of ≤ 5% was found for all conditions following both cue types.

RLpcN: Experiment 1 - probability of < 5% was found for the Lateral Target and No Distractor conditions following a neutral cue in both segments. Experiment 2 - in the first segment, probability of < 5% was found for the Lateral Target and Salient Target conditions following a neutral cue (Lateral Target following a valid cue = 0.06). In the second segment, probability of < 5% was found for all conditions following a valid cue and for the No Distractor and Salient Target conditions following a neutral cue (Lateral Target = 0.06)
